ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='Now I have a much clearer picture. Let me verify a few more things be
fore writing the final report.\n\nKey findings for this PR:\n\n**Blocking Issues
:**\n\n1. **OpenAPI MessageDto.status enum is incomplete** - The `im.yaml` chang
ed `status` from `[sending, sent, delivered, read]` to `[sent, read]`. But the b
ackend Gateway emits `message:delivered` events, and the mobile code handles `de
livered` status. The OpenAPI contract doesn\'t match the actual implementation. 
According to `api.md` section "契约漂移常见模式" Anti-Pattern #5: "消息状态机定
义不完整" - this is explicitly called out as a problem.\n\nWait, looking at the 
diff, it seems the original YAML had `[sending, sent, delivered, read]` and the 
PR changed it to `[sent, read]`. This is actually making the contract MORE incom
plete. The PRD says the status should progress from "sending" → "sent" → "delive
red", and the backend Gateway DOES emit `message:delivered`. So removing `delive
red` from the enum is a regression in the contract.\n\nActually, let me re-read.
The original had `[sending, sent, delivered, read]` and the PR changes it to `[s
ent, read]`. But `sending` is a client-side only state, so removing it from the 
server contract makes sense. However, `delivered` is emitted by the server via `
message:delivered` event. If `MessageDto.status` only allows `[sent, read]`, the
n the generated Dart/TS models won\'t deserialize `delivered` properly.\n\nWait,
looking at the gateway code:\n```typescript\nclient.emit("message:delivered", {\
n  client_message_id: payload.client_message_id,\n  sequence_id: result.message.
sequence_id,\n});\n```\n\nThe `message:delivered` event doesn\'t include a `stat
us` field - it includes `client_message_id` and `sequence_id`. So `delivered` is
not a value returned in `MessageDto.status` from the REST API. It\'s a separate 
WebSocket event.\n\nHowever, the PRD v1-im.md says:\n> And the message status sh
ould progress from "sending" to "sent" to "delivered"\n\nAnd the mobile code use
s `status: \'delivered\'` on messages. This is a client-side state derived from 
the `message:delivered` event. The server stores `status: \'sent\'` in the datab
ase.\n\nSo the server-side `MessageDto.status` can legitimately only be `[sent, 
read]` because those are the only values persisted in the database. The `deliver
ed` state is transient and communicated via WebSocket events.\n\nBut wait - the 
OpenAPI YAML is for the REST API, not WebSocket events. The WebSocket events hav
e their own documentation in `docs/api/socket-events.md`. Let me check that.\n\n
Actually, looking at `docs/api/socket-events.md`, I should verify if the `messag
e:delivered` event is documented there.\n\nLet me also check: is there a `docs/a
pi-contracts/im-events.yaml` or similar? The `api.md` says events should be in `
docs/api-contracts/<module>-events.yaml`.\n\nLet me read the socket-events.md fi
le.\n\n2. **Widgetbook registration missing** - The PR introduces 4 new design-s
ystem components (`sw_chat_bubble.dart`, `sw_chat_input_bar.dart`, `sw_conversat
ion_list_item.dart`, `sw_chat_message_list.dart`) but doesn\'t register them in 
`widgetbook/main.dart`. According to `flutter.md`: "新增组件必须在 Widgetbook 注
册": "每个 `atom`/`molecule`/`organism` 类都必须在 `widgetbook/main.dart` 中有至
少一个展示用例".\n\n3. **BDD step definition has empty implementation** - `im_re
al_time_message_delivery.steps.js` has an assertion for push notification that i
s just `assert.ok(true, \'Push notification service not yet implemented...\')`. 
According to `testing.md` section "Step Definition 禁止空实现": "`.feature` 文件
若使用 `autoBindSteps(feature, [commonSteps])` 而 `commonSteps` 中无对应实现，或
step 函数体为空（`() => {}`），则 BDD 测试会\'通过\'但不验证任何业务行为。**这是
无效测试**。" While this isn\'t exactly empty (it has a comment and assert.ok(tr
ue)), it\'s effectively a no-op assertion.\n\n4. **Conversation list cursor pagi
nation uses single-field cursor** - `getConversations` uses `updated_at` as curs
or. According to `api.md`: "对于高并发写入的列表（如会话列表、消息列表），必须使
用复合游标 `(updated_at, id)` 或 `(sequence_id, id)`，确保分页唯一性。" This is 
explicitly called out as a requirement.\n\n5. **SendMessageDto content validatio
n issue** - The DTO uses `@IsOptional()` and `@ValidateIf((o) => o.type === "tex
t")` on `content`. This means for `image` type, `content` is optional. But the s
ervice checks `if (dto.type === "image" && !dto.content)` and throws. For `syste
m` type, the service would NOT validate content at all (since ValidateIf only ch
ecks for "text"), but `system` messages DO need content. Also, the `type` field 
allows `system` in the enum, but system messages shouldn\'t be sent via the clie
nt API - they\'re created by the server. This is a security/validation issue.\n\
nWait, looking more carefully at the DTO:\n```typescript\n@IsIn(["text", "image"
, "system"])\ntype!: string;\n```\n\nThe `type` allows `system`, but system mess
ages are supposed to be created server-side only (via `createSystemMessage`). Al
lowing clients to send `system` messages could be a security issue. The service 
doesn\'t explicitly reject `system` type messages from clients.\n\nActually, loo
king at `sendMessage` service:\n```typescript\nif (dto.type === "text" && (!dto.
content || dto.content.length > 500)) {\n  throw ...\n}\nif (dto.type === "image
" && !dto.content) {\n  throw ...\n}\n```\n\nThere\'s no explicit handling for `
type === "system"`. If a client sends a `system` type message, it would pass the
validation (since `content` is optional for non-text types, and `type` allows `s
ystem`). Then it would be saved with `sender_id: senderId`, which contradicts th
e system message semantics (`sender_id` should be `null` for system messages).\n
\nThis is a real issue. The DTO should NOT allow `system` type for client-sent m
essages, or the service should reject it.\n\nActually, let me re-check the OpenA
PI contract:\n```yaml\ntype:\n  type: string\n  enum: [text, image, system]\n```
\n\nIt allows `system` in the REST API too. This is problematic.\n\n6. **Maestro
flow path issue** - `.maestro/flows/im/includes` is a symlink to `../../includes
`. Let me verify if this works correctly. The symlink points from `.maestro/flow
s/im/includes` to `../../includes`, which resolves to `.maestro/includes`. In th
e `send_message.yaml`, it uses `runFlow: includes/login-as-test-user.yaml`. Sinc
e the flow is in `.maestro/flows/im/send_message.yaml`, the relative path `inclu
des/login-as-test-user.yaml` would resolve to `.maestro/flows/im/includes/login-
as-test-user.yaml`, which via the symlink becomes `.maestro/includes/login-as-te
st-user.yaml`. This should work.\n\nBut wait - the symlink file in git might not
work the same way on all platforms. Let me check if it\'s properly committed.\n\
nActually, looking at the diff, `.maestro/flows/im/includes` is a new symlink. T
his is a reasonable approach.\n\nLet me now read socket-events.md to check the W
ebSocket event documentation.',
    encrypted=None
)
